A mouth-breathing academic.

18
00:00:55,512 --> 00:00:58,073
And unlike the other talks today that have been super,

19
00:00:58,113 --> 00:01:00,594
like really heavily grounded in hands-on techniques

20
00:01:00,654 --> 00:01:01,954
or practice or case studies,

21
00:01:02,614 --> 00:01:04,575
this talk is kind of about taking a step back

22
00:01:04,755 --> 00:01:07,476
and kind of reflecting on everything you've heard today.

23
00:01:10,857 --> 00:01:13,158
How am I gonna do this?

24
00:01:16,403 --> 00:01:18,944
So this talk is about analyzing level design

25
00:01:19,004 --> 00:01:20,444
in kind of a more critical sense,

26
00:01:20,524 --> 00:01:23,225
about going beyond ideas of layout or enemy placement

27
00:01:23,285 --> 00:01:24,886
as interesting and important as those are,

28
00:01:25,586 --> 00:01:27,246
and connecting it to kind of a bigger picture,

29
00:01:27,267 --> 00:01:28,047
at least trying to.

30
00:01:28,067 --> 00:01:30,468
It's about thinking about thinking, kind of.

31
00:01:31,480 --> 00:01:33,741
And if we can do that, then maybe we can get a better sense

32
00:01:33,781 --> 00:01:36,142
of what level design is and what level design might be

33
00:01:36,162 --> 00:01:39,264
in the future and maybe even open our mind

34
00:01:39,304 --> 00:01:41,305
to new ways of being level designers.

35
00:01:42,085 --> 00:01:43,526
And as with the other talks today,

36
00:01:43,546 --> 00:01:46,467
this talk is gonna have a heavy bias

37
00:01:46,507 --> 00:01:49,209
towards 3D games where you control a character.

38
00:01:49,229 --> 00:01:51,390
There's many other traditions of level design.

39
00:01:52,410 --> 00:01:54,431
Unfortunately, I'm not gonna talk about those.

40
00:01:58,852 --> 00:02:01,953
So let's imagine the world's most talented level designer.

41
00:02:04,014 --> 00:02:06,916
I did some computer modeling to generate

42
00:02:07,296 --> 00:02:10,198
what the greatest level design ever would look like.

43
00:02:11,018 --> 00:02:12,439
I couldn't find a picture of Liz England,

44
00:02:12,459 --> 00:02:13,700
so I just put a door there.

45
00:02:13,720 --> 00:02:14,980
There'll be Liz England.

46
00:02:16,581 --> 00:02:19,022
This person can generate 3D geometry with code,

47
00:02:19,042 --> 00:02:21,182
they can tell a story with careful prop placement,

48
00:02:21,422 --> 00:02:23,583
they can also manage a team of 20 people,

49
00:02:23,643 --> 00:02:25,543
but they also work really well alone,

50
00:02:25,603 --> 00:02:27,784
but they also sculpt subcontinents,

51
00:02:27,944 --> 00:02:31,484
but they also build cities made of several neighborhoods,

52
00:02:31,945 --> 00:02:33,465
but they also hand paint houses,

53
00:02:34,025 --> 00:02:36,246
and they also hand model the electrical cords

54
00:02:36,286 --> 00:02:37,206
for each house lamp.

55
00:02:37,766 --> 00:02:39,206
They did that and gone home, by the way.

56
00:02:40,955 --> 00:02:44,776
Does it really make sense that level design is all of these things?

57
00:02:45,496 --> 00:02:48,878
Because like every speaker you've come today, you've seen today,

58
00:02:49,618 --> 00:02:52,039
they were coming to level design from a really different angle

59
00:02:52,259 --> 00:02:53,640
and for a very different purpose.

60
00:02:53,740 --> 00:02:57,681
So why are we trying so hard to like unite all of these things

61
00:02:57,741 --> 00:02:59,102
under a banner of level design?

62
00:03:01,463 --> 00:03:03,483
So I want to complicate what level design is.

63
00:03:05,704 --> 00:03:08,205
Academics use the word complicate when we're going to talk a bunch.

64
00:03:09,946 --> 00:03:13,047
I'd like to propose four different ways of thinking about level design.

65
00:03:13,407 --> 00:03:17,089
There are actually infinite ways of thinking about level design, but 50 minutes, I'm just

66
00:03:17,109 --> 00:03:17,809
going to talk about four.

67
00:03:19,410 --> 00:03:21,771
In one sense, levels are just another piece of data.

68
00:03:21,871 --> 00:03:26,673
So what's level design as a form of material in a game?

69
00:03:27,253 --> 00:03:30,996
We can also think about the level designer as a job title in the game industry, as an

70
00:03:31,036 --> 00:03:32,117
industrial process.

71
00:03:32,958 --> 00:03:37,642
We can also think about level design as a theoretical branch of architecture, as well

72
00:03:37,843 --> 00:03:41,085
as an act of design and control within a community.

73
00:03:42,607 --> 00:03:46,610
And each level you make is interacting on all four of these dimensions.

74
00:03:46,690 --> 00:03:51,535
Every level you make is actually a hypercube, where each face of the cube is another cube.

75
00:03:51,595 --> 00:03:52,596
That's what a hypercube is.

76
00:03:57,246 --> 00:04:04,477
So first, let's think about level design as material and data in a really kind of literal sense.

77
00:04:04,577 --> 00:04:05,879
What is it on your computer?

78
00:04:08,334 --> 00:04:14,936
We can think of a level as a bunch of data or an asset that references a bunch of other assets.

79
00:04:16,937 --> 00:04:25,320
And in that case, a level editor might be software that visualizes this data as something really useful, friendly to humans.

80
00:04:25,620 --> 00:04:29,702
And it lets us construct or modify this data, ideally easily and effectively.

81
00:04:30,342 --> 00:04:33,423
So the question is, how do we fill these files with data?

82
00:04:33,523 --> 00:04:37,005
And how do we manage these complex connections between all these files?

83
00:04:39,454 --> 00:04:42,054
First, you could technically use a text editor,

84
00:04:42,194 --> 00:04:44,715
or Excel as your level editor, and a lot of people do this.

85
00:04:45,555 --> 00:04:47,375
The text on the left is actually data

86
00:04:47,435 --> 00:04:49,896
that is for a map file in Source Engine 1.

87
00:04:50,076 --> 00:04:52,296
It's just a series of keys and values.

88
00:04:52,776 --> 00:04:55,057
You could technically make a Counter-Strike Go map

89
00:04:55,157 --> 00:04:57,797
by just typing stuff in in Notepad or something.

90
00:04:58,238 --> 00:05:00,198
That'd be really awful, but I'm sure

91
00:05:00,238 --> 00:05:01,638
you could technically do it.

92
00:05:03,580 --> 00:05:06,642
And it's also worth knowing that not every game needs a dedicated level editor.

93
00:05:07,342 --> 00:05:10,565
You know, if you're working procedurally or if you have a small amount of possible tiles,

94
00:05:11,265 --> 00:05:13,927
it probably makes more sense to like code it or use text for this.

95
00:05:14,508 --> 00:05:18,411
You saw David Pimmons' talk earlier today about procedural level design for Eldritch

96
00:05:18,451 --> 00:05:20,332
and he showed the actual script files he does.

97
00:05:20,693 --> 00:05:23,235
He's using a text editor as a level design in that case.

98
00:05:28,556 --> 00:05:31,618
But so much of game development is about working with specialized tools.

99
00:05:31,878 --> 00:05:35,819
And if we study these tools, we can kind of sense there's like a tension often between

100
00:05:36,280 --> 00:05:37,920
data and a designer.

101
00:05:38,661 --> 00:05:41,182
So as an example, this is Arsenal 3.

102
00:05:41,262 --> 00:05:45,504
It's a StarCraft 1 modding tool that I used back in the day when I did StarCraft 1 modding.

103
00:05:46,524 --> 00:05:49,425
And notice that red checkbox there on the right.

104
00:05:49,505 --> 00:05:52,005
That red checkbox made me so angry.

105
00:05:53,386 --> 00:05:55,706
Because, you know, that red checkbox,

106
00:05:55,766 --> 00:05:58,387
if you don't check it, that means you don't have shields

107
00:05:58,667 --> 00:06:00,287
on that unit in StarCraft.

108
00:06:01,587 --> 00:06:03,148
Which made me upset, because I feel like

109
00:06:03,208 --> 00:06:05,488
if you just type in a number greater than zero

110
00:06:05,548 --> 00:06:07,589
into the shields box, can't you just assume

111
00:06:07,649 --> 00:06:09,389
I want shields on my Terran Marine?

112
00:06:09,869 --> 00:06:12,390
But if you uncheck it, it doesn't put shields on it,

113
00:06:12,410 --> 00:06:13,970
and it just ignores the number you put in there.

114
00:06:15,830 --> 00:06:19,491
That's just adding one more point of failure for me as a human being.

115
00:06:19,831 --> 00:06:20,992
It's just really terrible.

116
00:06:23,473 --> 00:06:25,793
So why can't the tool just check the box for me,

117
00:06:26,013 --> 00:06:27,454
or maybe even hide it entirely?

118
00:06:27,954 --> 00:06:31,055
So this is kind of what I mean by tension between data and designer.

119
00:06:31,615 --> 00:06:33,995
The StarCraft engine might have a very good reason

120
00:06:34,116 --> 00:06:37,556
for having a separate variable for needing that checkbox

121
00:06:37,596 --> 00:06:38,837
in the game data file format,

122
00:06:38,917 --> 00:06:41,938
but as a designer, do I really need to know about that?

123
00:06:43,680 --> 00:06:46,522
So this series of all these steps and stuff we have to do

124
00:06:46,622 --> 00:06:48,403
when working in a tool is called workflow.

125
00:06:49,324 --> 00:06:51,005
And a history of level editing tools

126
00:06:51,425 --> 00:06:53,106
would involve a history of workflow.

127
00:06:56,428 --> 00:07:02,013
So you might start in or the you might trace the origin of level editors back to AutoCAD in 1982

128
00:07:02,293 --> 00:07:07,038
That's what the original AutoCAD looked like I guess. I don't know I wasn't alive

129
00:07:07,058 --> 00:07:11,882
I was like a zygote or something a computer-aided design tool

130
00:07:12,303 --> 00:07:15,946
AutoCAD is a computer-aided design tool using industrial design architecture

131
00:07:16,987 --> 00:07:20,810
and the difference between AutoCAD and DoomEd on the right is that

132
00:07:22,412 --> 00:07:25,654
AutoCAD is really scary and making Doom levels is really fun.

133
00:07:25,934 --> 00:07:32,158
So Joel kind of touched upon this when he was talking about how modding made a lot of

134
00:07:32,198 --> 00:07:33,999
working with 3D really accessible.

135
00:07:34,540 --> 00:07:36,001
This is where level editors come into play.

136
00:07:36,041 --> 00:07:40,644
They're stripped down versions of really scary architectural drafting tools.

137
00:07:40,664 --> 00:07:43,166
So that's what's really nice about them.

138
00:07:44,006 --> 00:07:45,426
So on the right, there's DoomEd.

139
00:07:45,746 --> 00:07:47,427
That's the level editor used to make Doom 1.

140
00:07:48,467 --> 00:07:51,668
And notice that's just one big top-down 2D view.

141
00:07:51,728 --> 00:07:53,468
Doom is fundamentally a 2D game.

142
00:07:53,788 --> 00:07:55,749
There's no floor-over-floor construction.

143
00:07:55,769 --> 00:07:58,489
Well, I mean, now there is with the new engines and stuff.

144
00:07:58,529 --> 00:08:00,670
But before it wasn't possible.

145
00:08:00,690 --> 00:08:02,990
A bridge would not be possible in the original Doom.

146
00:08:03,891 --> 00:08:05,051
So you don't get really a sense,

147
00:08:05,531 --> 00:08:06,631
when you're working in DoomEd,

148
00:08:06,651 --> 00:08:07,832
you don't really get a sense of height.

149
00:08:07,872 --> 00:08:09,132
It's a top-down floor plan.

150
00:08:11,458 --> 00:08:14,981
So I think these days we kind of view this type of workflow

151
00:08:15,021 --> 00:08:16,942
as obsolete because it doesn't give us

152
00:08:17,102 --> 00:08:18,463
a good sense of height.

153
00:08:20,005 --> 00:08:22,046
But I kind of like it still a little

154
00:08:22,066 --> 00:08:23,648
because I think it places a lot of emphasis

155
00:08:23,708 --> 00:08:24,688
on lateral movement.

156
00:08:25,349 --> 00:08:27,351
You have really good sense of the organization

157
00:08:27,411 --> 00:08:28,411
of the general level here.

158
00:08:29,012 --> 00:08:33,034
A lot of people criticize modern FPS design as having really bad simple layouts.

159
00:08:33,334 --> 00:08:38,397
If you look at a single Doom or even a Wolfenstein 3D level, the layouts are like super complex

160
00:08:38,417 --> 00:08:41,559
and that's because they were thinking in terms of floor plan and layout.

161
00:08:42,939 --> 00:08:44,480
So maybe we can bring some of this back, I don't know.

162
00:08:47,104 --> 00:08:49,184
And even in that early DoomEd screenshot from 1992,

163
00:08:49,664 --> 00:08:51,485
you can see there was a texture browser.

164
00:08:51,785 --> 00:08:53,966
And this is something Jim Brown from Epic talked about

165
00:08:53,986 --> 00:08:55,987
in Level Design in a Day back in 2010,

166
00:08:56,647 --> 00:08:59,588
that a good asset browser is so important for your workflow.

167
00:09:00,688 --> 00:09:02,709
It might be weird to think of an asset browser

168
00:09:02,949 --> 00:09:05,830
as a technology that someone had to develop and design,

169
00:09:05,930 --> 00:09:08,491
but it's true, and here's an example of that.

170
00:09:09,451 --> 00:09:12,352
The model browser for the original Hammer Editor

171
00:09:12,412 --> 00:09:15,173
for Source One looked like the thing on the left.

172
00:09:16,074 --> 00:09:20,835
where it relied on thumbnail JPEGs to know what the model even was, basically.

173
00:09:21,655 --> 00:09:24,576
And you had to name it the same thing as your model file name and stuff.

174
00:09:24,596 --> 00:09:26,596
And it wasn't there, it just said MDL.

175
00:09:27,997 --> 00:09:32,778
This is really terrible, especially because Source actually embeds a lot of metadata into the models, too.

176
00:09:32,818 --> 00:09:34,899
It's really important to have a good browser here.

177
00:09:35,299 --> 00:09:36,419
And it was just really painful.

178
00:09:38,040 --> 00:09:41,121
So thankfully they updated their model browser

179
00:09:41,241 --> 00:09:42,082
to the one on the right.

180
00:09:42,162 --> 00:09:45,243
And real-time 3D preview is very common

181
00:09:45,423 --> 00:09:47,224
in most 3D tool sets these days.

182
00:09:51,652 --> 00:09:56,217
And then next, kind of like in the evolution of level editors, we can also talk about QuakeEd.

183
00:09:56,657 --> 00:09:58,339
This is the level editor for Quake 1.

184
00:09:59,440 --> 00:10:04,546
It's kind of the great ancestor of today's radiant family of level editors.

185
00:10:05,047 --> 00:10:06,689
And you can see two new features.

186
00:10:06,769 --> 00:10:07,089
There's a...

187
00:10:07,870 --> 00:10:09,532
3D camera preview in the upper left,

188
00:10:09,572 --> 00:10:11,074
that like blue blotch thing,

189
00:10:12,055 --> 00:10:14,458
as well as an elevation grid view.

190
00:10:14,898 --> 00:10:18,082
That's that thin white window to the right of the floor plan

191
00:10:18,563 --> 00:10:19,764
and that would show you the height

192
00:10:19,964 --> 00:10:21,446
of wherever you're currently building.

193
00:10:23,448 --> 00:10:25,128
And Radiant is kind of weird.

194
00:10:25,228 --> 00:10:27,269
No one really copies this thing anymore.

195
00:10:28,629 --> 00:10:29,910
And I don't know, I think Radiant's weird.

196
00:10:29,930 --> 00:10:31,830
Like why would you press space bar all the time?

197
00:10:31,850 --> 00:10:32,671
It's terrible.

198
00:10:32,811 --> 00:10:33,791
Okay, but anyway.

199
00:10:35,151 --> 00:10:37,632
The point is that this is kind of them transitioning

200
00:10:37,672 --> 00:10:39,853
from thinking about 2D floor plans

201
00:10:40,553 --> 00:10:43,934
to the true 3D thing that like Quake 1 offered, right?

202
00:10:48,750 --> 00:10:50,972
And a lot of what makes that possible is, again,

203
00:10:51,712 --> 00:10:53,694
much like how we didn't think of the asset browser

204
00:10:53,754 --> 00:10:56,616
as a technology, MouseGluck and WASD is actually

205
00:10:56,656 --> 00:10:59,498
a technology that we had to develop

206
00:10:59,598 --> 00:11:01,200
and it's now taken for granted.

207
00:11:01,900 --> 00:11:04,862
If you didn't have MouseGluck and WASD in our level editors,

208
00:11:05,223 --> 00:11:06,684
our levels would be a lot worse.

209
00:11:07,164 --> 00:11:09,506
Because if you talk to any level designer,

210
00:11:09,566 --> 00:11:10,907
or if you're a level designer yourself,

211
00:11:10,947 --> 00:11:12,809
you know that you'll spend five or 10 minutes

212
00:11:12,829 --> 00:11:15,431
just flying around your level, not really doing anything.

213
00:11:17,072 --> 00:11:20,756
And you'll feel really useless, like you're not really doing anything, but you're actually

214
00:11:20,776 --> 00:11:21,857
doing something really important.

215
00:11:21,897 --> 00:11:24,359
You're testing your level, you're testing the sense of space.

216
00:11:25,100 --> 00:11:26,161
And that's really important.

217
00:11:26,281 --> 00:11:31,626
It's almost kind of like this very conceptual, like situationist act where you're just drifting

218
00:11:31,686 --> 00:11:32,427
around your level.

219
00:11:32,447 --> 00:11:37,652
So you can say mouse look transforms us into like conceptual artists in a sense.

220
00:11:38,693 --> 00:11:45,422
Oh, and a fun fact, Autodesk only added WASD and MouseClick to AutoCAD in 2007.

221
00:11:46,083 --> 00:11:48,787
So be thankful you're not in that industry.

222
00:11:52,638 --> 00:11:57,259
And now we get kind of get to what we might recognize more as level editors these days

223
00:11:58,199 --> 00:12:02,780
This is the standard four pane view from 3d studio like one the first one in 1990

224
00:12:03,880 --> 00:12:06,081
And then here's also world craft in hammer

225
00:12:07,201 --> 00:12:10,322
I mean world craft or also known as hammer and also unreal ed

226
00:12:11,142 --> 00:12:17,284
And they still made heavy use of this arrangement where you have one 3d view and then three 2d orthographic views now

227
00:12:17,984 --> 00:12:21,845
And notice the 3d view is much more important than it was back in quake ed now

228
00:12:23,536 --> 00:12:25,437
And I think the grid views here are really important

229
00:12:25,497 --> 00:12:28,218
because when you're working in Quake lineage engines,

230
00:12:28,438 --> 00:12:29,459
there's something called a leak.

231
00:12:29,979 --> 00:12:33,780
And if you have a really small, one millimeter thin crack

232
00:12:34,141 --> 00:12:35,421
in the outer shell of your level,

233
00:12:36,682 --> 00:12:40,263
that crack will suck everyone in the game out to space

234
00:12:40,603 --> 00:12:42,764
and everyone will die and your level will break

235
00:12:42,804 --> 00:12:44,845
and the map compile process will break too.

236
00:12:44,865 --> 00:12:46,245
It's just really terrible.

237
00:12:46,626 --> 00:12:50,547
So you need really exact kind of solid manipulation here

238
00:12:50,567 --> 00:12:52,048
and that's what grid views offer.

239
00:12:52,588 --> 00:12:54,829
a lot of good accuracy when doing that stuff.

240
00:12:56,790 --> 00:12:58,011
This type of window layout, I think,

241
00:12:58,051 --> 00:12:59,572
is still supported in most packages,

242
00:12:59,692 --> 00:13:01,733
but it's no longer the default, I think.

243
00:13:02,914 --> 00:13:04,335
Instead, this is the default now.

244
00:13:06,234 --> 00:13:07,695
This is pretty much the standard setup now.

245
00:13:07,735 --> 00:13:10,436
It's one big interactive 3D view.

246
00:13:10,456 --> 00:13:14,338
