an architectural murder, kind of.

735
00:41:20,812 --> 00:41:24,533
I mean, they reached a compromise, and by compromise, I mean, they did their very best

736
00:41:24,593 --> 00:41:26,034
to destroy Myelin's design.

737
00:41:27,314 --> 00:41:33,396
So what they did is they wanted to put this big, tacky, bronze statue cast by Frederick

738
00:41:33,436 --> 00:41:37,818
Hart, he's the white guy in the upper right, to symbolize all the soldiers who died.

739
00:41:38,838 --> 00:41:43,019
But the whole point of the memorial was to communicate the sheer scope of all the lives

740
00:41:43,099 --> 00:41:43,400
lost.

741
00:41:44,500 --> 00:41:50,344
to give every soul some space and respect, to defy any co-optation of their lives by the government

742
00:41:50,684 --> 00:41:56,988
by refusing to reduce 50,000 lives to three symbolic figures of melting pot patriotism.

743
00:41:59,410 --> 00:42:04,433
But they did it anyway, and the statue is like right next to the memorial now, and it kind of

744
00:42:04,473 --> 00:42:10,196
ruins it. But as a final slap in the face, they paid the sculptor four times what they awarded to Mai Lin.

745
00:42:11,969 --> 00:42:14,051
So this is why modernism kind of died.

746
00:42:14,071 --> 00:42:20,136
Because even giant racists like Ross Perot, they have to admit that buildings are more

747
00:42:20,196 --> 00:42:23,019
than just their party, more than just their shape.

748
00:42:23,660 --> 00:42:28,945
Buildings also have their politics, and they might even be conservative politics too.

749
00:42:33,525 --> 00:42:35,346
So maybe it's not form follows function.

750
00:42:35,526 --> 00:42:38,669
Maybe it's more form follows worldview.

751
00:42:39,470 --> 00:42:42,232
You have to ask whose function are we following?

752
00:42:43,293 --> 00:42:44,534
What's the common language?

753
00:42:44,574 --> 00:42:46,595
Whose terms become the common language

754
00:42:46,636 --> 00:42:47,796
for an entire discipline?

755
00:42:49,198 --> 00:42:53,261
So therefore, form follows worldview,

756
00:42:53,321 --> 00:42:54,542
architecture is political.

757
00:42:55,323 --> 00:42:57,504
Listen and include the communities you build for.

758
00:42:57,544 --> 00:42:58,886
So here's some examples of that.

759
00:43:00,788 --> 00:43:08,431
This building is Inner City Arts in Los Angeles and there they provided an underserved neighborhood

760
00:43:08,471 --> 00:43:10,251
with arts programs and community events.

761
00:43:10,852 --> 00:43:15,513
They specifically chose to paint it white to show that they would invest and maintain

762
00:43:15,613 --> 00:43:17,614
in this building and infrastructure.

763
00:43:18,174 --> 00:43:23,496
They also kept the garage doors to kind of harken back to their past as a converted car

764
00:43:23,536 --> 00:43:25,316
garage in industrial Los Angeles.

765
00:43:27,077 --> 00:43:29,358
They also built the facility in several stages.

766
00:43:29,418 --> 00:43:33,380
You can see on the left, they just started with that core there and then they actually

767
00:43:33,420 --> 00:43:35,661
expanded it and added more buildings on later.

768
00:43:35,681 --> 00:43:39,343
So you can think of it as kind of early access architecture.

769
00:43:40,003 --> 00:43:43,425
They could immediately start making an impact and earn more funding and get the trust of

770
00:43:43,465 --> 00:43:45,806
the community before doing more with it.

771
00:43:50,408 --> 00:43:58,155
Another example here is the El Guadal Children's Center in Columbia, where, you know, building

772
00:43:58,195 --> 00:44:02,478
with prefabricated sheetrock and steel frames might make sense in New York, but it doesn't

773
00:44:02,498 --> 00:44:03,219
make sense here.

774
00:44:04,040 --> 00:44:05,701
So they used local building techniques.

775
00:44:06,302 --> 00:44:11,546
They cast the concrete with bamboo, local bamboo, and they also got local craftsmen.

776
00:44:11,566 --> 00:44:13,468
They trained the local craftsmen to do all this.

777
00:44:14,629 --> 00:44:17,231
And there's no big, expensive HVAC systems.

778
00:44:18,832 --> 00:44:22,635
They spent three years consulting with the community as to what they wanted and needed

779
00:44:23,095 --> 00:44:27,899
and the result was really wide sidewalks, a really large courtyard, bathrooms in every

780
00:44:27,939 --> 00:44:30,861
classroom so a student doesn't have to ask permission to go to the bathroom.

781
00:44:32,603 --> 00:44:38,047
So the postmodern critique of modernism might be that architecture must not just be site

782
00:44:38,067 --> 00:44:40,428
specific, it should also be community specific.

783
00:44:43,758 --> 00:44:47,220
Next there's also the Quinta Monroy housing development in Chile.

784
00:44:48,241 --> 00:44:53,424
A firm was hired by the government to renovate a neighborhood popularly named by squatters.

785
00:44:54,704 --> 00:45:00,047
So instead of evicting the squatters and building a condo or something or replacing with a housing

786
00:45:00,087 --> 00:45:04,250
project, they actually talked to them and found out what their needs were and what they

787
00:45:04,290 --> 00:45:04,590
wanted.

788
00:45:06,291 --> 00:45:10,315
And they actually turned their limited budget, too, into a design strength.

789
00:45:10,615 --> 00:45:15,459
Rather than build an entire project at a low and cheap standard, they chose to just build

790
00:45:15,599 --> 00:45:16,400
half of a house.

791
00:45:16,880 --> 00:45:20,343
But that half of a house was an entry-level, middle-class living standard.

792
00:45:20,944 --> 00:45:25,628
And then the squatters are used to improvising their own structures and building structures.

793
00:45:25,688 --> 00:45:30,432
So they made use of that, and they let the residents fill in the rest of the building

794
00:45:30,552 --> 00:45:32,554
as they need it, according to their own needs.

795
00:45:33,374 --> 00:45:37,137
And that way it's kind of they're making the neighborhood their own still,

796
00:45:37,917 --> 00:45:41,380
improves their living conditions, and you're sharing control over the

797
00:45:41,400 --> 00:45:44,122
appearance and structure of neighborhoods with the architects.

798
00:45:48,485 --> 00:45:52,288
So there's already kind of a rich tradition actually of post-modern level

799
00:45:52,328 --> 00:45:57,351
design existing in video games. So I kind of want to highlight that.

800
00:45:59,143 --> 00:46:01,685
So a lot of post-modern level design comes from modding

801
00:46:01,725 --> 00:46:02,905
and multiplayer communities.

802
00:46:03,986 --> 00:46:06,427
There on the very left is a notorious map

803
00:46:06,467 --> 00:46:08,367
called Achievement All V4.

804
00:46:09,568 --> 00:46:11,329
So in Team Fortress 2, they had this thing

805
00:46:11,349 --> 00:46:13,750
where you could get achievements to get items.

806
00:46:13,810 --> 00:46:15,931
So people started grinding achievements

807
00:46:16,991 --> 00:46:18,832
and idling in servers where they could

808
00:46:18,872 --> 00:46:20,773
just grind achievements in order to get items.

809
00:46:21,293 --> 00:46:23,834
So what happened was all these achievement grinding maps,

810
00:46:24,274 --> 00:46:26,895
and then someone made an achievement trap map.

811
00:46:27,355 --> 00:46:29,698
where it's all these players playing in the achievements,

812
00:46:29,778 --> 00:46:31,119
grinding achievements, blah, blah, blah.

813
00:46:31,419 --> 00:46:34,322
And after a few minutes, a giant cat comes out of the ground

814
00:46:34,583 --> 00:46:37,325
and then shoots lasers at everyone and kills everyone

815
00:46:37,686 --> 00:46:40,448
and keeps killing them and then nukes the entire level

816
00:46:40,649 --> 00:46:43,071
and punishes them all for grinding for achievements.

817
00:46:44,672 --> 00:46:45,872
It's really beautiful.

818
00:46:45,952 --> 00:46:48,273
It's a really beautiful map.

819
00:46:48,733 --> 00:46:52,434
And then their second is a map called Surf Thunderboom.

820
00:46:53,294 --> 00:46:57,235
Surf map and surf map culture is a really interesting thing that's coming out of the

821
00:46:57,315 --> 00:46:59,375
CS Counter-Strike community.

822
00:47:00,336 --> 00:47:02,016
And it's this really beautiful architecture.

823
00:47:02,156 --> 00:47:04,637
It's all these surreal kind of slanted shapes.

824
00:47:05,037 --> 00:47:07,217
Very unusual in FPS level design.

825
00:47:07,557 --> 00:47:11,198
Maybe like Quake 3 floaters are the nearest analog maybe.

826
00:47:12,606 --> 00:47:18,667
And then next there's FY Ice World, which is a very notorious map played in countless land cafes.

827
00:47:19,647 --> 00:47:22,848
And it's, by our terms, a really bad map.

828
00:47:23,108 --> 00:47:27,109
But it doesn't matter, because it fit a need within a community, and they're going to play it anyway.

829
00:47:27,449 --> 00:47:29,950
Instead of like, D.E. Paranessi or something.

830
00:47:31,970 --> 00:47:36,091
So the idea of an achievement trap, or a surf map, or a fight yard ice world map,

831
00:47:36,591 --> 00:47:39,592
those came more from players, not from developers.

832
00:47:41,736 --> 00:47:46,460
Or we can also consider maps like the Gary Hudson project, there on the lower left.

833
00:47:46,621 --> 00:47:49,884
That was a marriage proposal made in the form of a Portal 2 map.

834
00:47:51,225 --> 00:47:52,707
Or the next one is Love Punks.

835
00:47:52,887 --> 00:47:57,271
That's an amazing game made in collaboration with Neighbourhood Kids in rural Western

836
00:47:57,351 --> 00:47:57,912
Australia.

837
00:47:59,433 --> 00:48:04,078
It imagines game development as a kind of community mural kind of thing.

838
00:48:05,782 --> 00:48:09,985
Or we can talk about the work going on in countless schools that use Minecraft as a teaching tool.

839
00:48:10,325 --> 00:48:12,446
So, you know, how did Greek architecture work?

840
00:48:12,506 --> 00:48:17,109
Well, let's try to build a Greek temple and we'll find out a lot about how Greek architecture worked.

841
00:48:18,009 --> 00:48:20,329
What matters more is the story around the level, right?

842
00:48:20,349 --> 00:48:21,549
The process of making it.

843
00:48:22,730 --> 00:48:24,890
Playing the Portal 2 marriage proposal

844
00:48:26,150 --> 00:48:29,351
might be an okay level, but what we care more about is,

845
00:48:29,631 --> 00:48:31,772
oh, did he make it himself as a labor of love

846
00:48:31,812 --> 00:48:32,952
or did he pay someone to do it?

847
00:48:33,912 --> 00:48:36,013
Did the person say yes or no, right?

848
00:48:36,373 --> 00:48:38,773
Those are more important than what the actual puzzle

849
00:48:38,893 --> 00:48:41,114
in the Portal 2 marriage proposal was, right?

850
00:48:41,554 --> 00:48:43,814
So what matters is the process, the context,

851
00:48:43,874 --> 00:48:45,815
not so much the actual puzzle

852
00:48:45,875 --> 00:48:47,615
or game mechanic stuff going on.

853
00:48:47,755 --> 00:48:53,880
here. And again, these are all rich traditions of level design that exist

854
00:48:53,920 --> 00:48:57,583
outside of Steam storefronts and Humble bundles and I think it's

855
00:48:57,623 --> 00:49:01,126
important we acknowledge how much happens outside of our developer bubble.

856
00:49:05,356 --> 00:49:09,899
So I'd like to end this talk with a discussion of what might be the future of level design.

857
00:49:10,460 --> 00:49:12,001
What will level design look like?

858
00:49:12,822 --> 00:49:16,044
What other alternate level designs can we imagine?

859
00:49:16,825 --> 00:49:22,710
This is a picture by a speculative architect named Libas Woods.

860
00:49:23,451 --> 00:49:25,812
If you're not familiar with him, you should look up his work.

861
00:49:26,113 --> 00:49:31,577
Chances are your favorite sci-fi movie in the last five years stole shamelessly from

862
00:49:31,617 --> 00:49:31,938
his work.

863
00:49:35,778 --> 00:49:39,179
So I want to imagine three possible level design futures.

864
00:49:40,020 --> 00:49:42,440
There are in reality an infinite amount of futures,

865
00:49:42,540 --> 00:49:44,341
blah, blah, blah, but these are just the three

866
00:49:44,361 --> 00:49:47,122
that I can kind of semi-coherently describe.

867
00:49:47,202 --> 00:49:49,883
So, and they're already happening right now.

868
00:49:51,043 --> 00:49:52,964
And they'll continue to happen probably.

869
00:49:55,985 --> 00:49:57,845
So first, industrial.

870
00:49:59,130 --> 00:50:03,393
I'd characterize industrial level design as the main ideology of the AAA game industry.

871
00:50:04,274 --> 00:50:08,678
Here we see attempts at a lot of universal theories, things like the idea of like a vista

872
00:50:08,858 --> 00:50:13,661
and all your maps should have vistas every now and then, or Ubisoft has something called

873
00:50:13,721 --> 00:50:17,645
rational game design where they kind of put a lot of their games through that kind of

874
00:50:17,725 --> 00:50:18,145
framework.

875
00:50:19,406 --> 00:50:22,750
Or even when you're working on Sunset Overdrive and you come up with a thing called a bouncy,

876
00:50:22,950 --> 00:50:23,170
right?

877
00:50:24,512 --> 00:50:27,775
You're coming up with your formalism, you're coming up with your grammar, and it's the

878
00:50:27,835 --> 00:50:29,257
developers dictating that.

879
00:50:32,660 --> 00:50:36,224
But I mean, it doesn't always apply to things like...

880
00:50:38,716 --> 00:50:40,297
Does Gone Home have vistas?

881
00:50:40,917 --> 00:50:43,178
Does the concept of vistas really apply to Gone Home?

882
00:50:43,198 --> 00:50:44,579
Because you're inside all the time.

883
00:50:45,479 --> 00:50:46,600
Or what about Dear Esther?

884
00:50:46,640 --> 00:50:48,461
Does the concept of vistas apply to Dear Esther?

885
00:50:48,481 --> 00:50:50,422
Dear Esther's 100% vistas, right?

886
00:50:50,802 --> 00:50:53,503
It's almost like redundant to call out

887
00:50:53,563 --> 00:50:54,784
every vista in that game.

888
00:50:56,325 --> 00:50:58,906
So, you know, these grammars, I would argue,

889
00:50:58,966 --> 00:51:00,987
are often problematic and can't be applied

890
00:51:01,047 --> 00:51:03,908
to any game, just lazily.

891
00:51:05,082 --> 00:51:08,863
And over time, I also think we're going to see increased specializational labor.

892
00:51:08,923 --> 00:51:12,104
So already we're seeing absurd things like a content designer.

893
00:51:12,164 --> 00:51:15,105
What's a content designer?

894
00:51:15,125 --> 00:51:15,945
What's content?

895
00:51:16,365 --> 00:51:21,246
Maybe job titles you can get so specialized, there's going to be a junior rock rotator.

896
00:51:21,266 --> 00:51:23,327
That person will just rotate rocks and levels.

897
00:51:23,367 --> 00:51:25,407
Or a tree intern.

898
00:51:25,747 --> 00:51:27,588
They rotate the trees and your levels.

899
00:51:29,408 --> 00:51:31,549
Junior trash placer.

900
00:51:32,229 --> 00:51:34,649
You know, like, will labor get more specialized?

901
00:51:34,849 --> 00:51:38,350
Maybe. It'll depend on the changing nature of AAA games, I guess.

902
00:51:39,310 --> 00:51:43,691
So industrial level design imagines level design as this fundamentally human-oriented thing.

903
00:51:44,331 --> 00:51:47,312
The solution to better levels is for humans to think better,

904
00:51:47,512 --> 00:51:50,133
or to put more humans to work on the problem.

905
00:51:50,453 --> 00:51:52,873
And that's generally how you solve problems within this mindset.

906
00:51:54,064 --> 00:51:57,327
The critique of this is that it's kind of pretending postmodernism never happened.

907
00:51:57,907 --> 00:52:01,951
It's kind of pretending you can just kind of work your way out of things when maybe

908
00:52:01,971 --> 00:52:05,475
you might have to adopt a different approach or a different kind of formalism.

909
00:52:10,058 --> 00:52:13,101
Future B might be what I call cyborg level design.

910
00:52:14,562 --> 00:52:16,884
You know, much like how there are different programming languages,

911
00:52:16,964 --> 00:52:19,846
all with their different strengths and weaknesses, there are a lot of different ways

912
00:52:19,886 --> 00:52:22,208
to generate levels and code simulations of levels.

913
00:52:22,228 --> 00:52:23,028
So...

914
00:52:26,520 --> 00:52:29,762
You'll often hear them talk about them,

915
00:52:29,822 --> 00:52:31,743
I mean like Proc Gen, level designers,

916
00:52:31,783 --> 00:52:33,904
talk about this framework worked for this problem.

917
00:52:34,165 --> 00:52:36,586
Prim's algorithm worked for this thing in Eldritch,

918
00:52:36,886 --> 00:52:38,867
but I had to modify it for this other thing.

919
00:52:39,127 --> 00:52:40,388
But when I'm making this new game,

920
00:52:40,448 --> 00:52:41,689
I'm not gonna use Prim's algorithm

921
00:52:41,709 --> 00:52:43,009
because that didn't work for this.

922
00:52:43,810 --> 00:52:46,491
So you see kind of multiplicity of different formalisms,

923
00:52:46,511 --> 00:52:49,473
and these are all just tools instead of one formalism

924
00:52:49,513 --> 00:52:51,254
that you just use for the entire game maybe.

925
00:52:53,385 --> 00:52:56,807
And the concept of a cyborg is kind of funny, you know, like we usually think of cyborgs

926
00:52:56,887 --> 00:53:01,589
as something like the Borg from Star Trek, full of all these invasive implants.

927
00:53:01,609 --> 00:53:04,350
But a lot of theorists argue that we're already cyborgs.

928
00:53:04,971 --> 00:53:08,112
The way we use smartphones, they might as well be implanted in our hands.

929
00:53:09,593 --> 00:53:11,874
We've been using books to augment our memory.

930
00:53:12,215 --> 00:53:13,815
We use wheels to augment mobility.

931
00:53:14,956 --> 00:53:19,218
To a certain sense, a cyborg isn't a technological construct, it's a social construct.

932
00:53:20,399 --> 00:53:25,643
So that's what leads us into the politics of human machine authorship.

933
00:53:25,983 --> 00:53:29,425
You know, what is a good procedural level generation algorithm?

934
00:53:29,865 --> 00:53:31,206
Well, it depends, right?

935
00:53:32,027 --> 00:53:37,151
But I think a lot of people would say good procedural generation output would ideally,

936
00:53:37,191 --> 00:53:40,953
like the most perfect one, would resemble human authored output.

937
00:53:41,554 --> 00:53:46,517
You wouldn't be able to tell the difference between procedural generation and handmade human generation.

938
00:53:48,077 --> 00:53:49,417
But why should we do that?

939
00:53:49,437 --> 00:53:51,318
Well, if we judge procedural generation

940
00:53:51,398 --> 00:53:53,659
on its different terms.

941
00:53:54,039 --> 00:53:56,120
And I think that's what David was getting at

942
00:53:56,140 --> 00:53:57,200
in his Eldridge talk.

943
00:53:57,240 --> 00:54:00,181
He was talking about how he was aiming for semi-coherency

944
00:54:00,461 --> 00:54:03,002
and he was involving Lovecraft Cthulhu stuff.

945
00:54:03,082 --> 00:54:05,423
So that means the levels didn't have to look

946
00:54:05,443 --> 00:54:08,324
like they were hand built because it works

947
00:54:08,444 --> 00:54:10,445
when they're not totally elegant.

948
00:54:13,490 --> 00:54:18,556
And currently I don't think of this as a very like AAA kind of domain because I think it

949
00:54:18,576 --> 00:54:23,221
needs immediate, AAA usually needs immediate payoff and they don't want to invest in long-term

950
00:54:23,261 --> 00:54:26,785
research or if they do they treat it as a trade secret and not tell anyone.

951
00:54:27,726 --> 00:54:31,330
So I think this is mostly an academic or indie endeavor for now.

952
00:54:35,305 --> 00:54:38,007
And then the last feature I want to talk about might be local level design.

953
00:54:39,048 --> 00:54:43,372
What if we made levels that were just for our clan, for our multiplayer server, for

954
00:54:43,452 --> 00:54:44,793
our school, for our church?

955
00:54:46,154 --> 00:54:49,217
What if levels were community murals that told our collective stories?

956
00:54:49,738 --> 00:54:52,400
What if we made marriage proposal levels?

957
00:54:53,160 --> 00:54:56,043
What if we made levels just to give as small gifts to each other?

958
00:54:58,205 --> 00:55:02,407
Local level design is characterized by rejection of top-down formalism.

959
00:55:03,708 --> 00:55:08,250
If the purpose of a level is to deceive its players and make for really good YouTube fodder,

960
00:55:08,270 --> 00:55:12,632
how does that change the structure of a level, right? You're not going to be thinking in terms

961
00:55:12,692 --> 00:55:16,414
of choke points, you're going to think in terms of what will look cool on YouTube or something,

962
00:55:16,434 --> 00:55:18,155
or what will PewDiePie like or something.

963
00:55:19,608 --> 00:55:24,129
Local levels speak to things outside of video games.

964
00:55:24,189 --> 00:55:25,510
They speak to ourselves.

965
00:55:26,270 --> 00:55:27,871
They imagine level design, game development

966
00:55:27,911 --> 00:55:29,672
as something we do for specific people,

967
00:55:30,012 --> 00:55:33,313
not an abstract player derived from market research.

968
00:55:34,553 --> 00:55:36,554
Local levels are process oriented.

969
00:55:36,974 --> 00:55:38,515
